text: What about a movie about an unborn child who is headed for abortion by its mother and another adult (father?) who loves that child as much as this film shows love for a child.  Why is it that a child in the making has been ruled by American government to be a thing and not a child?  All this emotion here for the precious child - what about some emotion for the child-to-be?  Doesn't he or she count as much?  I don't get it.  Oh, yes I forgot - it's convenient to get rid of the potential child.   Well, I couldn't give birth and adopted a wonderful baby boy who is grown now.  He is loved and valued by all who know him.  But he could just as easily have been cut apart in the womb.   Very sorry, got carried away.  Alicia Vikander is wonderful and I'm sure I'll enjoy this... thinking those thoughts all the time.

text: This is one of those overly ambitious movies that carries heavy burden on its shoulders and can't quite handle it. Talking about positives first i must say it is well directed and acted, beautifully shot and quite interesting for the most time. It raised some heavy questions and i like that aspect. Unfortunately it is jumbled and unevenly paced that it feels rushed in the beggining and drawn out in the middle.Characters were not developed that well and you do not feel so much for them and their pain plus combining their dumb decisions with melodrama that bites so hard during the film, it gets quite underwhelming. There are also unanswered questions in the end and kinda cheesy sendoff but if you are rom drama junkie and you need your fix then you could go far worse than this. 3/5
